<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-182-288  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 182 288.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Which Computer?andP;  Feb 1990 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Time bomb program helps promote security issues.andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The bizarre mass mailing of AIDS information program disks thatturned out to be a hoax has triggered new concern about computersecurity.andP;  A legislator in the United Kingdom's House of Commonsintroduced a bill as one measure to help stop computer crime.andP;  TheAIDS disk did not turn out to be as destructive as it firstappeared to be, but it did shake the confidence of a number ofusers who feared for their data.andP;  The problems many users had withthe pernicious disk could have been avoided if there had been abusiness policy on the handling of unsolicited software.andP;  Anantidote for the AIDS program is available for free from PCBusiness World.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United KingdomComputer CrimesComputer VirusesData SecurityInsurance Policy HandlingLegislation.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>